{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625139"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:21:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:21:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17007"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17007"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68216"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9697"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53673"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"11092"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22829"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68216"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging (MRI) is based on the behaviour of hydrogen nuclei in tissues when exposed to strong magnetic fields and radiofrequency pulses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the physical basis of magnetic resonance imaging?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reflection of ultrasound waves from tissue interfaces","Detection of gamma radiation from radioactive tracers","Alignment of hydrogen nuclei in a magnetic field","Measurement of electrical activity in tissues","Absorption of X-ray radiation by tissues"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMRI works by using \u003Cstrong\u003Ealignment of hydrogen nuclei in a magnetic field\u003C/strong\u003E. When placed in a strong magnetic field, hydrogen nuclei (protons) align either parallel or antiparallel to the field. Radiofrequency pulses then temporarily disturb this alignment, and the return to equilibrium produces signals that are used to create images.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other imaging modalities:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReflection of ultrasound waves from tissue interfaces\u003C/strong\u003E describes the principle behind ultrasound imaging, where sound waves bounce off interfaces between tissues with different acoustic impedances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of gamma radiation from radioactive tracers\u003C/strong\u003E is the basis of nuclear medicine imaging, where radioactive isotopes are administered and their decay is detected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasurement of electrical activity in tissues\u003C/strong\u003E refers to diagnostic tests that record bioelectric signals such as electrocardiography or electroencephalography.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsorption of X-ray radiation by tissues\u003C/strong\u003E is the fundamental principle of radiography and computed tomography, where X-ray beams are differentially absorbed by tissues of varying densities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe signal in MRI comes from the behaviour of protons during two types of relaxation: T1 relaxation (return to longitudinal magnetisation) and T2 relaxation (loss of transverse magnetisation). Different tissues have different relaxation properties, which creates contrast in the images.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Magnetic resonance imaging uses strong magnetic fields to align hydrogen nuclei in tissues.","T1 relaxation represents the time taken for protons to realign with the main magnetic field.","T2 relaxation represents the time taken for protons to lose phase coherence with each other."],"references":["Aagesen AL, Melek M. Choosing the right diagnostic imaging modality in musculoskeletal diagnosis. Prim Care. 2013;40(4):849-viii. doi:10.1016/j.pop.2013.08.005"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53673"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17007"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53673"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T15:15:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T15:17:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9697"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68216"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","posi